Frustrated with the bed leveling procedure on your new Replicator? Thought you got it level only to have your print fail the first layer or not bond on one side? I believe the 4 screw leveling design and the difficulties with achieving a truly level build plate are the root of many user's build problems. They certainly were for me. With this jig and a dial/digital indicator you can get your build table as level as is possible. You can also use this to find out if your build plate is warped! Video procedure at http://youtu.be/hgWeew6SmjQ UPDATED: 2/12/2016 Extended back tab and added another magnet to give it more stable "clamping" to the X axis rails. Made magnet holes pass all the way through to allow you to push the back the other way if necessary. Included 3D Systems Geomagic and step CAD files if you want to modify for your needs or fix a weakness in my design.

This procedure is a work in progress. I have done this on mine and my print quality and first layer bonding to the build table are the best they have ever been. Your mileage may vary. This may sound very complicated but if you have any machinist experience it should be relatively straight forward. I will try to add photos later to augment the thousand words here. It might be easier to perform the standard Replicator leveling and then fine tune it with the Digital Indicator and this jig. I have started doing this after I heat the build plate as I have seen to plate go way out of level after heating. UPDATE 5/21/2012: I consistently see the front of the build plate droop about 0.3mm-0.4mm when the plate is heated to 100C. That's pretty much the diameter of the filament and is definitely enough to mess up a build. I suspect the plastic bed support arms are softening slightly in the heat. Now I always preheat my plate and then check level, being careful of course not to burn myself! Builds are consistently good now with 0.2mm layer height. Watch your extruder nozzles throughout this procedure - don't crash them into your build plate!
  • Print this jig. I used 25% fill, 0.2mm layer height, bed temp 110C, nozzle temp 227C, 1 shell.
  • Install 0.25" Diameter X 0.25" thick magnets ( http://www.amazon.com/Magcraft-NSN0617-4-Inch-Magnets-20-Count/dp/B000SQK2JK/ref=pd_cp_hi_1 ) just flush with surface in their respective holes. See magnet install picture http://www.thingiverse.com/image:136277.
  • Carefully insert digital indicator into the top center 0.375" hole. It is a press fit. If your bonding between layers is not good it might crack. Don't push it all the way in just get it started.
  • My Pittsburgh (Harbor Freight 93295) Digital Indicator has 1" of travel. I seated it in the jig such that there is a gap of 0.34" between the top of the jig and the bottom of the Digital indicator body (See gap photo http://www.thingiverse.com/image:136278). We want the dial indicator seated such that the needle just starts to move when the jig is installed with the build table in the home (top) position and the jig attached to the X axis rails. The build table deflects easily with very little pressure so if the dial indicator is set too far down its spring force will deflect the table down and cause measurement errors.
  • Before you install the jig on the X axis rails, use the Replicator Home Axes from the Utilities menu to send the build plate to the top Home position.
  • Put the nozzle(s) over the back right corner nearest that leveling screw. I used a 0.001" shim (I happened to have paper that thickness). I'm an not sure about this thickness yet. I might want it a little thicker? I got some feeler gauges ( http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005689P7A/ref=oh_details_o00_s00_i01 ) and will test some different thicknesses.
  • Adjust the back of the build table till the nozzle just "bites" the shim when you pull it. This is your reference height. Makes sure there is no plastic sticking from extruder nozzle as this will mess up your measurement.
    • NOTE: Watch it when you move your nozzle(s) for the next steps - don't crash them into the table before it is leveled. Move them to the far left to keep them off the work surface and out of the way for the rest of the procedure.
  • Now place the jig on the X axis rails with the Dial indicator needle facing down toward the table. You should feel the magnets click the jig in place. It should sit flat and steady - no wobble.
  • Carefully move the X and Y axis and slide the indicator jig such that the indicator tip is just forward of the back right build plate leveling bolt (See home zero picture http://www.thingiverse.com/image:136276). Don't put the indicator tip on the bolts. Put it on the plate somewhat close to the bolt. The indicator tip should contact the table and move up slightly.
  • Carefully zero the digital indicator without pushing up or down.
  • Now go to each leveling bolt starting with the back left one so the nozzle(s) stay off the build plate.
  • Adjust the leveling screws to get close to zero on each. It takes a light touch on the leveling screws - pushing up or down even slightly on then shows up on the gauge.
    • NOTE: 3 points in space is a plane, 4 points is a pain! Because there are 4 leveling screws you will find that you get 3 right and then you get to the 4th and it seems to mess things up. Get it close and then check the other 3 again, it took me a couple passes at first becuase my table was out of whack but now it is easier to get it back into shape. NOTE2: If you have OCD like me you'll want all corners exactly zero. This will drive you nuts. Remember 0.03mm is less than 0.0012". Don't get too carried away. UPDATE: 5/22/2012 I don't follow my own advice - I keep going till I get all zeros anyways!
  • Now enjoy the high quality printing you expected from your Replicator!
    • UPDATE: I added a 3D CAD file in .igs format exported from Alibre 3D for those you want to modify this to fit their own indicator. UPDATE 7/9/2012: I added a version 2 with a V shape for the back rail, elimianated the superfluous hole in the side and leveled the contact points front and back. Also added version 2 with the harbor freight 5/16" magnet holes ( http://www.harborfreight.com/10-piece-rare-earth-magnets-67488.html ). I undersized the holes by 1/64" so hopefully a press fit. I have not printed the new version yet.

title: Which 3D software should I learn for 3D printing?

description.text:
[update] Added: FreeCad and Autodesk Fusion 360.
-- At our MakerSpace, I am often asked for advice about what should someone use in order to create 3D objects for 3D printing.
There is not just one single answer because it depends on a few parameters so I made a little decision chart:
http://www.gliffy.com/go/publish/5271448 Please share your choices and advices in the comments. The 3D files are there as exemples:
  • The octopus is a Typical exemple of what you would use an the softwares on the left side for (organic shapes).here it was with Blender.
  • The "central part" is a typical exemple of what you would use the softwares on the right for (precise dimensions). Here it was with Cubify Design
    • Disclaimer:
    It is certainly not exhaustive or objective but it is based on quite a lot of reading, interviews and experiences.
    This is a troll-friendly subject so please stay constructive in your suggestions to improve this decision tree.

description.text:
I use a Tianchen TC-158N robot lawn mower because I'm to lazy to mow by hand.
This robot comes with two blades which are crap. You will never get them really sharp and they are pretty loud.

So I started to design some kind of blade holder. This one here works best for me. It uses three blades (the common ones for Automower, Gardena etc.) per disk. You need two disks for this lawn mower.

The disks fits perfekt on the motor shaft. You don't need to change anything on your mower, just unscrew the crappy blades and srew these here on.

BOM for one Tianchen mower

  • 2 printed disks
  • 6 sharp blades with M4 screws (like Automower)
  • 6 RAMPA inserts (https://www.schraubenking.at/M4-x-8mm-Rampa-Muffe-Typ-A-Stahl-verzinkt-P003788) to mount the blades

There are two versions for blade disks. One is more high and will cut your grass lower. I used the flat one and it works pretty well.

ARDUMOWER
Because I didn't like the behavior of the mower itself (software) and I'm a maker, I replaced the whole electronics and software with an arduino.
If you want to build up your own mower (yes, it is possible) or replace the electronics of any kind of robot mower (yes, this is possible too) because it is damaged or doesn't work good, visit www.ardumower.de
Here you find everything needed like software, examples, tutorials, forum, plans etc.

Printer:

Sparkcube

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

50% or more

Notes:

You should use ABS or PETG for printing. PLA might also work but I want a material which doesn't crack if the disk hits stones.

You should also use high Infill rates, like 50% for strength. Also you should use at least 5-6 perimeters.

Installation
  1. First screw the RAMPA Inserts into the disks. I used a M4 screw and nut for this. Put the nut on the screw and both into inserts. Now screw the nut downwards to insert so everything is tighten. Now you can screw the insert into the disk.

ATTENTION: Don't attacht he blades right now. This is the last step.

  1. Now replace the original Tianchen crappy blades with the disks (without the razor sharp new blades!)

  2. You can now run a first test with the mower. Lift the mower or lay it on one side. Be sure it can't move, the wheels must be able to move free.
    Now start your mower (if possible only the mow motors, I use my own board and software, so i can start the mow motors without starting the whole mower).

BEWARE: The mower will start working. Please don't hurt yourself. This might be dangerous.

  1. Listen: do you hear any noise or vibrating sound? In this case, you first check, if disks are properly attached. If they shake up and down, there is some derbs between motor shaft and disk. If they shake left-right, follow next step.

  2. If your disk shake, you have to balance the disks. This can easily be done with a rasp or file. PLEASE: again don't do this with sharp blades attached. Put you mower on one side and ensure it can't move when you start the mower.
    Now start the mower, so the mow motors will turn. Bring the file or rasp slowly on the disk. This must be done from one side (left or right, see example here http://wiki.ardumower.de/index.php?title=Datei:Chassis_m%C3%A4hscheibe_auswuchten.jpg). The file will rasp print material away so the disk will become more and more round. Stop when the noisy vibrating sound is gone.

  3. Stop the mower and attach the really sharp new blades.

  4. Mow

description.text:
VERY MUCH IN DEVELOPMENT AND USE AT YOUR OWN RISK! DO NOT HANG YOUR EXPENSIVE LENSES FROM IT SHOULD YOU TRY TO MAKE IT! DO NOT BLAME ME IF YOU BUST A LENS!

A little more complicated build as you will need to 3D print some parts, buy in some bolts and screws and do a bit of metal work to produce the mounting plates and belt buckle.

This device is hooked on your belt. The idea is there is always one lens mounted on it, a second on your camera. So, to change lens, remove from your camera and clip into the open spot on the device, then remove the other lens and put on camera. This way you don't have to put a lens down.
VERY IMPORTANT: If you decide to make this the bolt must have a LOCKNUT. The pins must be made from metal as must the top and bottom mounting plates and the BELT BUCKLE. I am going to fashion the pins from stainless steel nails I have and manually cut the mounting plates from Aluminium. The springs are just generic ones I have lying around but it is important that it has a smaller diameter than the pin head. There is an image showing where the pins and springs goes.

DO NOT 3D PRINT THE BOLT, NUT, SCREWS, SPRINGS, PINS, BELT BUCKLE and MOUNTING PLATES as I have included those only to give an overview of how the devcie comes together and they must all be made from metal. The mounting plates should be used as a paper template only. They are a Nikon F-Mount but may need a bit of fine tuning.

The bolt is based on a McMaster-Carr part but I found Zenith brand stainless steel bolt M5 x 20mm and M5 locknut locally. The McMaster parts are 90576A104 and 92005A322.
The 10 screws, also based on McMater-Carr ( 90065A151) but again I found a Zenith 6G x 18mm stainless steel part locally.

Note at this point the holes sizes and counter sunk dimensions for the 10 screws in the mounting plates are wrong and I have not bothered to fix it as I will eyeball it when I make them as you want to ensure the screw heads can't scratch your lens mounts so the counter sunk will be adjusted accordingly.

There is a commercial device like this available but I do not own one, nor is this directly copied from it. In fact, I've never seen one in the flesh. If I am breaching copyright, please let me know and I'll remove it. It's just that I have wanted one from the first time I saw it on the web so I thought I'd give it a go myself.

Depending on how well your printer is dialed in you might have to adjust the print size a little (1 or 2 percent over or undersized). I suggest you use the "Test Section.stl" file for testing fitment, it'll save you time and filament as it's only one "wing" of the spinner.

My settings were:
.2 layer height
2 shells
3 top and bottom solid layers
10% fast honeycomb infill
no raft, no supports
1 layer, 1 shell skirt (for priming purposes)

Batteries

The design is meant to be used with CR2032 batteries. They are widely available and can be found in cheap 8 packs at Ikea for instance. Positive side goes up.

LEDs

I'm using 5mm LEDs. The shorter pin goes on the bottom, underneath the battery. Bend it ever so slightly so that it makes proper contact with the battery.

The other lead (positive) goes on top and needs to be bent so that it provides proper contact with the battery when latched under the ridge on the edge of the compartment. See pictures.

Center Bearing

The design calls for a standard 608 style bearing. eBay or Amazon is your best bet. Any 608 will work but apparently the ceramic ones will provide the longest spin times. I've found that normal 608 bearings over time will get longer spin times too as the grease runs thinner. YMMV though.

Button caps

I haven't included any caps since there are too many out there already. I personally like mine a little concave to give me some proper grip. I suggest you use these (as I did):
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2071591

Design

I designed this from scratch using Autodesk Fusion360. No I will not hand out the original design files.

title: Pen Plotter attachment for CNC chucks

description.text:
This is an attachment that lets you turn your CNC mill into a pen plotter without any modifications.
The attachment has a stalk that the chuck can grip just like a drill bit or endmill. I've included two versions, one with a plastic stalk and one with a hole for a machine screw (#5 diameter, 1.5 inches or longer) in case the plastic stalk is too weak.

I printed this on a Replicator with 20% infill and at a feed rate of 30 (I find the slower feed rate makes slightly longer build times but much more repeatable results). All the other settings were unchanged.
Print the part, insert a pen (it should be able to press-fit pretty tightly, but I'm also planning on adding hooks so a rubber band can be used to tension the pen against the paper), re-zero your Z-axis, and start drawing!
I designed this to allow clearance between a Dremel flex attachment and the upright pen, but you may need to lengthen the piece in Sketchup if you're using a regular Dremel (alternately, you could find a short pen...).
This part is listed as "in progress" because I haven't tested it yet (I'll have to do that when I get back to my mill at home). I expect to update the part with improvements and extra features, but no radical changes.

title: Mini dual Y adapter for E3D V6 style hotend with bowden extruders

description.text:
Inspired by the Dagnall Y Extruder.
The coupling is roughly 4cm tall and mounts directly on the alu heat sink.

Bottom pneumatic coupling drilled through and sawed off top part to save space. Ridges sawed on the hex nut part to ensure the plastic is able to get a good grip. Heated and pressfitted in place.

1mm holes for superglue to secure PTFE tubing and bottom coupling (use a needle to help it penetrate). Might be overkill.

Recommend if necessary drilling through the alu heatsink with a 4mm drill to widen the hole and get the PTFE tube down to the heat break barrel (mine did not have that feature), and cut the tubing to length for a tight fit down there when screwed in place.

Minimum retraction needed for filament switching is about 8cm - but to avoid headaches use 10+.

Seems to be very robust - easily survived many filament crashes caused by bad gcode/slicing. Even survived several hard crashes where an angry gorilla was trying to "help"/force the filament through when the extruder started grinding plastic - for obvious reasons... Dual extrusion without a mixing head is hard.

Some gcode snippets/hacks that worked for me (11cm retraction, direct drive extruder).
Code assumes the second extruder filament is down in the hotend, and first filament halfway down the pneumatic coupling/at the end of its bowden tube.
Startup:
T1 ;Select second tool. Expect this to be down in the hotend
G92 E0; Reset extruder
G1 E-110 F4200; Retract T1 to park position
T0 ;Select first tool, expect to be roughly in the park posiition and push down into heatbliock
G92 E0; Reset extruder
G1 E90 F3000; Advance T0
G92 E0; Reset extruder
G1 E20 F400; Advance T0 slowly and hope it extrudes some filament...
G92 E0; Reset extruder

Slic3r custom tool change gcode:
T[previous_extruder]
G92 E0
G1 E-110 F4200
G92 E0
T[next_extruder]
G92 E0
G1 E110 F4200
G92 E0

title: Anet A8, easy removable extruder cooling fan

description.text:
I have made this mod to make i easy to access the extruder for clearing jams. It also helps alot when loading flexible filament to be able to see in to the extruder gear and heatbreak opening.

With this mod you can just "slide" the extuder fan in and out, without any tools.


~~~~~~~~~~~~
This mod includes cutting down the extruder heatsink. My subjective observation are that the incresed airflow more than fully compensates for this and making the extruder run at least as cool at stock. But be aware that all modding are at your own risk!
~~~~~~~~~~~~

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I printed this part in ABS (to have good heat resistance) and at 100% infill, as the part is so small an weight about 4 grams anyway. Probably less infill and other materials work good as well.

I used supports in touching buildplate mode in cura, to avoid supports blocking up the holes.

Mounting the mod

You need to use shorten M3 screws to mount this part instead of the stock fan moutning. I shorted my origial screew to approx. 30mm threaded length.

I have cut of the heatsink so it only covers the lover part of the extruder when it has contact to the metal part it boltet to (see pictures). This allows the access to the extruder and better airflow.

To make my extruder more compatible to flex filaments, I also did rise the heatbreak until it almost touches the feeding wheel. Sinde then i had zero flex filament jams :-)

description.text:
My very first thingi! Cord hangers that go into the Joy-Con slots of Nintendo Switch.

With the cord attached from two points on each side it's easy to hang Switch from pretty much anywhere in an angle. I'm personally using these on my bed for rather comfy gaming experience.

These came out so nicely even with my first prototype that there was no need to add any kind of locking mechanism. When slotted, they are stiff enough to hold Switch's weight even when bouncing it from the hangers with fingers.

I can't guarantee that the size will be perfect with other printers with varying settings so be prepared to have a file or sand paper nearby.

I don't know why you would need an eight-sided die that uses 1, 2, 3, and 0, but if you do, here it is.

This is a solder reel holder for my 500g reel of solder. The print (1 file) contains 2 objects - the main body of the holder and feed hole, and the spindle. It is a lovely little compact holder, which functions surprisingly well. I originally had concerns about the feed hole being too small but it seems to feed absolutely fine - even with kinks in the solder.

No supports, rafts, brims, etc. needed to print this (at least, on my XYZ DaVinci Jr. - other printers may vary).

Took my DaVinci Jr. just over 5 hours to print the entire file.

Tools and Software I Used:
  • Vernier Calipers
  • Pen and Paper
  • Sketchup Make 2017 (free edition, with STL export plugin)
  • XYZware Printer software
  • DaVinci Jr. 1 with Neon Green PLA filament
Steps

  1. Measured dimensions of solder spool and centre hole. Measurements noted down for later reference

  2. Created a basic 5mm frame, with a small wire feed guide at the front. Then created a spindle slightly longer than the width of the main frame.

  3. Created a semi-circle cut-out in the middle of the side walls with a 1mm bigger radius than the spindle.

  4. Save, Export to STL

  5. Import STL into XYZware - ensure that object fits print bed. Settings were 30% infill, good quality, normal speed. No supports/rafts/brims.

  6. Export final file to SD card and pop into printer.

  7. Hit the start button to commence building

  8. Enjoy the hypnotic movement of the machine

  9. You now have one rather lovely solder holder!

description.text:
Servo mount for (very cheap) ball valve, 6.35mm (1/4") variant.
Direct coupling which is press fitted and screwed to the servo, and press fitted/clamped down on to the ball valve rod.
Using standard 20Kg metal gear servos with 20x40mm (horisontal plane) housing, and M5 bolts for clamping/rigidity,
Tested with PLA and PTFE - both works nice/ seems more than rigid enough. Will probably use PLA for the "production batch" since it can print a lot faster.

Pic shows a pneumatic control jig with separate servos on inlet and exhaust, a pressure sensor and the fill/flush line.
Why 2 servos instead of single one with multi port ball valve you say - reason: cheap prototyping and had some of the hardware available in the junk box :)

description.text:
We are a Creative Agency, and so some of us, like to do some urban sketching. Since, we like our tools to get out of the way, we decided to design a small watercolor set that would be very portable, durable and smart.

This is the result of some trial and error. Hope you'll like it.

Features:

  • the "halfpans" normally used in such situations are square, but that is mostly due to the methods of production, since this palette is made for being filled with tubes than we could go with more user friendly roundish shape
  • the four magnets (5 x 5 x 2 mm) glued to the back make for a perfect stabilization for the palette. This way you can use it straight from the box, take it outside and stick it to the front of open box unveiling the whole sponge or make any other semi-permanent connection with the box
  • the palette has got a small handle to make it easier for taking it out of the box.
  • the size of pans is just our decision and you are free to modify it, but we thought that it would be nice to have some bigger pans for mixing, or for the color you use most often

The kit we use:

  • the 3D printed palette with neo-magnets glued with some Superglue (cyano acrylate glue)
  • Kaweco fountain pen box (12 x 5,5 x 2,3 cm) with extra enamel white paint inside for better mixing;
  • KOI waterbrush (size Medium) with the cap shortened a bit and glued back;
  • Face washing sponge cut in half to fit inside the box;
  • Winsor & Newton watercolor paints but that is just your decision
  • Extra magnet for using when painting standing. Just put it beneath the previous page and put the whole box on top of that page. The box will clamp to the magnet on the other side of paper and will stay in that position even when you tilt the sketchbook.
  • some elastic for making sure that the box doesn't open inside your bag after heavy usage (not really needed since the box closes tight - just extra safety)

also a Micron Pigma fineliner (01 on this photo), Leuchtturm pen holder and Moleskine Watercolor pocket.

description.text:
This is my project to make sturdy 3d-printed arms, witch have a length of 400mm. With more arm length the copter will be more stable in the air. This design include 2 separate arms connected with 2 bolts and nuts. In case of a bad crash with damage to one of the arms you just print out the piece that you need. Let me know what your thoughts are with this design. Its already printable, but i am thinking of separate 'legs' which absorb the landing and easily snap off when you hit the ground too hard. Separate legs will reduce the amount of damage on the arms, but are another 4/8 parts you need. What you think about that? UPDATE 21-02-2014
Added a arm for mounting on the DJI base plate UPDATE 18-02-2014
Updated the normal 'Arm 1' because of a faulty bolt pattern. UPDATE 14-02-2014
Added arms with motor mount holes for Tiger MN3510, one with leg and one whitout, also the other arm without leg

Print both arms with at least 50% infill to make them sturdy and durable.  
You'll need 2 bolts and nuts (to connect the arm parts), M4 with at least 40mm lenght.

comments.text: I've 3d built and fly my F450 crossfire a lot.   But this baby is EPIC and takes warp drive to get her in the air.  With Tiger 3510's she weighs in 5lbs empty and 7 lbs with 2 big lipos.  The 3d print probably costs at least 1-2 lbs compared to carbon but it worth it for glory sake IMO.   With 3510's I can still carry another 3 lbs if needed.   And yes, each arm took about 3 hours to print on my BFB3000.   I only print PLA since ABS warping has left me scarred for life!

description.text:
Fidget Spinner. Looks good,but spin is off a bit because of the lack of radial symmetry. I originally made this in 2 parts (top and bottom) and then glued them together, but the top piece has to be printed with supports. That worked pretty well, but I wanted to make one without supports so I made the 1 piece.

I put in a common 22 mm (skateboard) bearing.

The bearing is greasy and will slide out if you use it a lot or get rough. You might clean the grease off of the outside to help it stay longer, but I just used the Simple Bearing Cap from Very Customizable Fidget Spinner to make it easier to hold and to keep your fingers grease free.

description.text:
This is a 3D Printer Project i wanted to build because the current nice priced 3D Printers were great, @ $150 up to $200 for a standard 220x220x240 or 8"x8"x9" or 8"x8"x11". However the parts i needed printed require printing in sections.
And for most of my Major Parts that would be 8 parts @ 4 hour prints or 32 hours of printing.
So i decided to use my other 2 3D Printers as parts to make a larger and extra strong 440x440x300 Printer where i can print the parts i need in one print.
So i am using my Remaining Delta Kossel 180x330 Printer to print the parts i need.
So all the prints listed in the Project were made on the Delta Kossel printer which i will be upgrading to a 330x330 printer.
I'm also going to use and remix current Anet, Tronxy and Pursia Printed parts and mod them to work with my Project.

as of 5/24/2017: Final got the printer put to together, did a dry run and worked great.
now i have to print a few more items, enclose it and it will be ready to start printing my Comic-Con items in 1 print.
Next project will be to upgrade or make my Kossel Delta Printer Larger. from a 180x300 up to 220 maybe even 330.

As of 5/31/2017:
Printer is working and printing my larger Items.
The above printer all parts were made from ABS at 240 Hotend, 110 Hotbed and .2 mm at 80 % infill with a .5 mm Tip.
Final part is a 1/2 inch PVC Frame with Corrugated side panels.
I've replaced the old Thermostat with a 25A Expansion Board General Heated Bed http://www.ebay.com/itm/172569448851
Final step will be to add extra Lighting inside the cabinet with a remote camera to view progress. I'm sure everyone here knows how to add extra Lighting and a camera for remote viewing. So there will ne no need to add them.

Good luck in your build, Hopefully this project will help you decide what you need.

I've added a video link so you can see the printing process.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ccp7_7hjijc&t=4s

Design Steps

Designing a printer from Scratch isn't easy. But I have experience in building several items from nothing to street legal, example: Electric Motorcycle, Electric Car, Full Size Dalek for Comic Con.
Anyway.
i placed the 440x440 Diamond plate on the ground and marked center. moved plate forward and backwards till i got the size that was required to print in this plate.
That is how i came across a 24"x24"x30" Square box.
Once all the wiring and mounting is done i will be enclosing this Printer in its own case to keep as much heat in as possible and keep the wind/air flow done to almost nothing, since we all know to much cool air will warp printed items.

description.text:
This pulleys give me more precise printing, nearly without backlash issue. In addition I tested them with TMC2100. Due to gear ratio 14 : 24 they give less load to TMC driver, It could produce maximum 1.7A . This combination prints nearly noiseless.

I have those setting in Merlin firmware:
#define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {115.49, 115.49, 4266.66, 150 }

(200*16)/(19*2.5)*(24/14) = 115.49
200 - 1.8' stepper motor (360' / 1.8' = 200)
19 - teeth on pullesy
2.5 - belt type (2.5mm between teeth)
16 - because TMC2100 with 16 micro steps instead 32 (DVR8825)
24/14 - because double pulley has 24 teeth and 14 has motor's pulley
